{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510256"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:26:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:26:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11511"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11511"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.81,0.03,0.06,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84346"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"},{"type":"tags","id":"1903"},{"type":"tags","id":"2860"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35352"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man developed acute left great toe pain two days ago and has been receiving indomethacin for management of presumed gout flare. The pain has reduced significantly since. However, he developed acute right knee pain this morning and has now presented to the Emergency Department. He is unable to mobilise due to the pain and denies any trauma to the knee. His medical history includes hypertension, heart failure, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His usual medications include metformin, empagliflozin, perindopril, and simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 150/80 mmHg, pulse rate 110/min, SpO2 98% on room air, temperature 38.6\u00b0C, and respiratory rate 12/min. His left toe is mildly erythematous with minimal tenderness on palpation. The right knee is erythematous, swollen, and tender on palpation. He is unable to extend or flex his right knee due to swelling and pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to establish the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum uric acid level","Arthrocentesis","X-ray of the right knee","Blood cultures","Ultrasound of the right knee"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute, severe swollen right knee with associated pain and fever. The differentials include gout flare, hemarthrosis, septic arthritis, and pseudogout. These disorders can occur concurrently. While his metabolic diseases are risk factors for gout, it is important to recognise immunosuppression (e.g., type 2 diabetes mellitus) as a risk factor for septic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArthrocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is a crucial investigation to establish a definitive diagnosis of gout and to exclude other differentials such as septic arthritis. This is very important for patients without a previous history of gout or in whom the diagnosis is uncertain. This patient is immunosuppressed, tachycardic, and febrile, hence septic arthritis needs to be excluded. The key arthrocentesis findings in important differentials are summarised as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Egout: monosodium urate crystals, which are needle-shaped and negatively birefringent under polarising light microscopy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epseudogout: calcium pyrophosphate crystals, which are rhomboid-shaped and positively birefringent under polarising light microscopy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eseptic arthritis: elevated leucocyte count (usually \u003E50,000 x 10^6 cells/L, predominantly neutrophils), positive gram stain and/or culture\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum uric acid\u003C/strong\u003E level may be low to normal during a gout flare. It is more helpful to measure this after resolution of the gout flare and for monitoring urate-lowering therapy (targeting \u003C0.36 mmol/L for most patients and \u003C0.30 mmol/L for those with tophaceous gout). It is also important to recognise that not all individuals with hyperuricaemia will develop gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eimaging\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g., x-ray and ultrasound) may help, it is not adequate for the definitive diagnosis of gout and exclusion of important differentials such as septic arthritis. Radiographic changes associated with gout (e.g., bony erosions due to tophi) may only occur in later stages. In the setting of septic arthritis, while imaging may be useful for detecting effusions, arthrocentesis confirms the diagnosis and is useful for guiding antimicrobial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in identifying systemic infection, especially in febrile patients, but they do not provide specific information about the joint pathology itself. Arthrocentesis remains the priority to directly assess the joint fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Arthrocentesis is a crucial investigation to diagnose gout and exclude other differentials (e.g., septic arthritis, pseudogout).","Septic arthritis is a key differential in immunosuppressed patients presenting with joint pain and systemic symptoms.","Monosodium urate crystals, which are needle-shaped and negatively birefringent, are seen in gout."],"references":["Shiozawa A, Szabo SM, Bolzani A, et al. Serum Uric Acid and the Risk of Incident and Recurrent Gout: A Systematic Review. J Rheumatol 2017; 44:388.Shiozawa A, Szabo SM, Bolzani A, Cheung A, Choi HK. Serum Uric Acid and the Risk of Incident and Recurrent Gout: A Systematic Review. J Rheumatol. 2017 Mar;44(3):388\u201396. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28148699/","McQueen FM, Doyle A, Dalbeth N. Imaging in the crystal arthropathies. Rheum Dis Clin North Am. 2014 May;40(2):231-49. doi: 10.1016/j.rdc.2014.01.004. Epub 2014 Feb 20. PMID: 24703345. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24703345/","Richette P, Doherty M, Pascual E, Barskova V, Becce F, Castaneda J, Coyfish M, Guillo S, Jansen T, Janssens H, Liot\u00e9 F, Mallen CD, Nuki G, Perez-Ruiz F, Pimentao J, Punzi L, Pywell A, So AK, Tausche AK, Uhlig T, Zavada J, Zhang W, Tubach F, Bardin T. 2018 updated European League Against Rheumatism evidence-based recommendations for the diagnosis of gout. Ann Rheum Dis. 2020 Jan;79(1):31-38. doi: 10.1136/annrheumdis-2019-215315. Epub 2019 Jun 5. PMID: 31167758. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31167758/","Dalbeth N, Gosling AL, Gaffo A, Abhishek A. Gout. Lancet. 2021 May 15;397(10287):1843-1855. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(21)00569-9. Epub 2021 Mar 30. Erratum in: Lancet. 2021 May 15;397(10287):1808. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(21)01010-2. PMID: 33798500. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33798500/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84346"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16598"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16598","links":{"s